## Step-by-Step Integration

### 1. Copy Generated Files

```bash
# From the directory containing this file:
VHAL_DIR=$AOSP_ROOT/hardware/interfaces/automotive/vehicle/aidl/impl

# Create bridge directory
mkdir -p $VHAL_DIR/bridge

# Copy all generated files (including SDK subdirectory)
cp -r . $VHAL_DIR/bridge/
```

### 2. Replace VehicleService.cpp

```bash
# Back up the original
cp $VHAL_DIR/vhal/src/VehicleService.cpp \
   $VHAL_DIR/vhal/src/VehicleService.cpp.orig

# Install our replacement
cp VehicleService.cpp $VHAL_DIR/vhal/src/VehicleService.cpp
```

### 3. Modify the VHAL Service Android.bp

Edit `$VHAL_DIR/vhal/Android.bp`. Find the `cc_binary` target for the VHAL
service (named `android.hardware.automotive.vehicle@V*-default-service`).

**Add** `BridgeVehicleHardware` to `static_libs` and **remove**
`FakeVehicleHardware`:

```diff
 cc_binary {
-    name: "android.hardware.automotive.vehicle@V1-default-service",
+    name: "android.hardware.automotive.vehicle@V1-default-service",  // keep existing name
     vendor: true,
     defaults: [
-        "FakeVehicleHardwareDefaults",
         "VehicleHalDefaults",
         "android-automotive-large-parcelable-defaults",
     ],
     ...
     static_libs: [
         "DefaultVehicleHal",
-        "FakeVehicleHardware",
+        "BridgeVehicleHardware",
         "VehicleHalUtils",
+        "libjsoncpp",
     ],
     ...
+    required: ["flync-DefaultProperties.json"],
 }
```

> **Note:** The binary name (`@V1` or `@V3`) varies by tag. Do NOT change it.
> The existing `vintf_fragments` and `init_rc` references stay unchanged.

### 4. Build

```bash
cd $AOSP_ROOT
source build/envsetup.sh
lunch <your-automotive-target>

# Build just the VHAL module (includes bridge + daemon)
cd hardware/interfaces/automotive/vehicle/aidl/impl
mma
```

### 5. Deploy to Emulator

```bash
# Start emulator with writable system
emulator -writable-system &

# Wait for boot, then push
adb root
adb remount
adb push $OUT/vendor/bin/hw/android.hardware.automotive.vehicle@V*-default-service \
         /vendor/bin/hw/
adb push $OUT/vendor/bin/flync-daemon /vendor/bin/
adb push $OUT/vendor/etc/automotive/vhal/DefaultProperties.json \
         /vendor/etc/automotive/vhal/
adb push $OUT/vendor/etc/init/flync-daemon.rc /vendor/etc/init/

# Set SELinux permissive for initial testing
adb shell setenforce 0

# Restart VHAL
adb shell stop vehicle_hal_server 2>/dev/null; adb shell stop vendor.vehicle.hal.default
adb shell start vendor.vehicle.hal.default
```

### 6. Verify

```bash
# Check VHAL service is running with bridge
adb logcat -s BridgeVHAL:* VehicleService:*

# Check daemon is running
adb logcat -s FlyncDaemon:*

# Check properties are registered
adb shell dumpsys car_service | grep -i "property count"
```

## Vehicle Body SDK

The `sdk/` directory contains the Vehicle Body SDK files, copied verbatim from
the reference implementation. These files handle:

- **COM layer** (`com/`): Signal bit-packing/unpacking and buffer management
- **CAN I/O** (`can_io/`): Wire format serialization
- **Signal API** (`app/swc/`): High-level `get_*()` / `set_*()` functions

The daemon calls `get_*()` to read RX signal values and `set_*()` to write TX
signal values. The SDK's COM layer manages the underlying UDP transport and
PDU buffers -- the daemon does not need its own transport implementation.

> **Important:** Do NOT modify the SDK files. They are maintained separately
> and should be updated by replacing the entire `sdk/` directory.

